                text: "Water on Earth is always moving in a cycle that never stops. This process is called the water cycle. It has four main stages: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and collection. First, the Sun heats water in oceans, lakes, and rivers. This heat turns liquid water into an invisible gas called water vapor. This is evaporation. The water vapor rises into the sky. As it goes higher, the air gets colder. The cold air turns the vapor back into tiny water droplets. This is condensation. These droplets join together to form clouds. When the droplets become too heavy, they fall back to Earth as rain, snow, sleet, or hail. This is precipitation. Finally, the water collects in oceans, lakes, rivers, and underground. This is collection. Then the cycle starts all over again. The water cycle is important because it gives fresh water to all living things. The same water that dinosaurs drank millions of years ago is still being recycled today.",
