                text: "Social media has changed how people communicate around the world. Platforms like Instagram, TikTok, and YouTube let anyone share content with millions of people. But have you ever wondered how these apps actually work? When you post a photo or video, it gets stored on huge computers called servers. These servers are kept in massive buildings called data centers. Some data centers are as big as shopping malls and use as much electricity as small cities. Algorithms decide what content to show you. An algorithm is like a recipe that a computer follows. Social media algorithms track what posts you like, how long you watch videos, and what you search for. Then they show you more similar content to keep you interested and scrolling. Companies make money through advertising. Advertisers pay to show you ads between posts. The more time you spend on the app, the more ads you see, and the more money the company makes. That is why apps are designed to be hard to put down. Understanding how social media works helps you make smarter choices about how you use it. You can control your experience instead of letting algorithms control you. Setting time limits and being picky about who you follow can make social media more positive.",
