                text: "Deep in the ocean, where sunlight cannot reach, creatures make their own light. This remarkable ability is called bioluminescence, and it transforms the dark sea into a spectacular light show. Scientists estimate that ninety percent of deep-sea animals can produce light. Bioluminescence occurs through a chemical reaction inside an animal's body. Two substances‚Äîluciferin and luciferase‚Äîcombine with oxygen to create light without heat. Unlike light bulbs, which waste energy as heat, bioluminescent light is incredibly efficient. Animals use this ability for many purposes. Anglerfish dangle glowing lures to attract prey. Firefly squid flash patterns to communicate with mates. Some jellyfish release glowing clouds to confuse predators while escaping. The deep-sea dragonfish uses red light that most animals cannot see, essentially giving it invisible night vision. Scientists are studying bioluminescence for human applications. Medical researchers have inserted bioluminescent genes into cells to track diseases. Others are developing biological lighting that could replace electricity. Most exciting, bioluminescence helps scientists explore new ecosystems. Researchers recently discovered a 'twilight zone' in the ocean where bioluminescent creatures live in numbers far greater than previously imagined.",
