                text: "Nobody wanted to confront Jackson about his drinking. He was popular, funny, the guy who made every party memorable. But Maya had watched her best friend's transformation over eighteen months‚Äîthe brilliant athlete becoming unreliable, the honors student failing classes, the kind person turning mean when intoxicated. When Jackson missed his sister's recital because he was passed out, Maya decided enough was enough. She researched intervention strategies, consulted with a school counselor (without naming Jackson), and recruited a small group who cared about him beyond his party persona. The intervention was brutal. Jackson's initial reaction was rage‚Äîdenying the problem, accusing them of betrayal, storming out. Maya had been warned this might happen. The counselor advised patience and consistency: maintain boundaries, express concern without enabling, let consequences accumulate. Weeks passed without apparent progress. Then Jackson crashed his car into a mailbox, thankfully harming no one. His parents, confronting undeniable evidence, arranged professional treatment. The recovery wasn't linear. Jackson relapsed once before finding stable sobriety. Some friendships survived; others didn't. He and Maya remained close, though their dynamic shifted fundamentally. She'd seen him at his lowest, had refused to pretend everything was fine, had loved him enough to risk the friendship. Jackson later told her that moment‚Äîwhen friends gathered to say 'we see you struggling'‚Äîwas when he first admitted to himself that he needed help.",
