                text: "The episodes began after Rosa's near-drowning accident. Without warning, she would experience moments from the past‚Äînot her own past, but the history of whatever location she occupied. In her school's gymnasium, she witnessed a 1950s basketball game. In a coffee shop, she watched a robbery that newspaper archives confirmed had occurred in 1978. The experiences were overwhelming but harmless until she visited the old Pemberton house. The moment she stepped inside, Rosa collapsed into a vision so intense it blurred the boundary between observation and participation. She experienced the night of December 14, 1943, from the perspective of Charlotte Pemberton, who was hiding her brother‚Äîa military deserter‚Äîin the basement when military police arrived. Rosa felt Charlotte's terror, her desperate lies, her heartbreak when soldiers dragged her brother away. When Rosa regained awareness, she found herself in the basement, having apparently walked there unconsciously during the vision. In the corner, beneath rotted floorboards, she discovered a metal box containing letters Charlotte had written to her brother‚Äîletters never sent because he was executed before they could reach him. Rosa delivered the letters to Charlotte's descendants, now elderly themselves. They'd never known the full story‚Äîonly family whispers about wartime tragedy. Reading their great-aunt's words, they finally understood her lifelong sadness. Rosa realized her strange ability served a purpose: she was a bridge between past and present, carrying unfinished stories to those who needed them.",
