                text: "Internships at prestigious museums were supposed to be boring‚Äîfiling, cataloging, fetching coffee. Nobody expected eighteen-year-old Lucia to uncover a conspiracy that had deceived art experts for decades. But when her assigned task involved comparing high-resolution photographs of the museum's prized Vermeer painting with conservation records, she noticed an anomaly that more experienced eyes had missed. The pigment analysis from 1987 showed Prussian blue in areas where the restoration report claimed original Dutch ultramarine existed. Prussian blue wasn't invented until 1704‚Äîdecades after Vermeer's death. The painting couldn't be authentic. Lucia brought her discovery to Dr. Morrison, the conservation department head, expecting praise. Instead, she encountered carefully controlled panic. Further investigation revealed the painting had been acquired in 1962 under circumstances now clearly suspicious. If the forgery was exposed, the museum faced not only embarrassment but potential criminal liability for unwitting involvement in fraud. The decision whether to disclose fell to the board of directors, who initially preferred continued silence. Lucia, horrified by this complicity, faced her own ethical dilemma: respect institutional hierarchy or demand transparency. After weeks of internal debate, she prepared documentation for an anonymous submission to an art crime investigative journalist. Before sending it, she gave Dr. Morrison final warning. The museum announced the painting's questionable provenance voluntarily‚Äîframing the discovery as institutional integrity rather than scandal. Lucia learned that powerful institutions often need external pressure to choose honesty.",
