                text: "Ivy had maintained the facade for years‚Äîstraight-A student, varsity athlete, student council president. Nobody suspected that she spent most nights unable to sleep, plagued by anxiety so intense it felt like drowning. That she sometimes couldn't eat for days because her stomach knotted with nameless dread. That she'd researched suicide methods not from intent but from a desperate need to know options existed. Her breaking point came during a college interview when she blanked completely, unable to recall achievements she'd practiced discussing. The interviewer's concerned expression‚Äîwas something wrong?‚Äîfinally cracked her armor. She heard herself saying words she'd never spoken aloud: 'I think I need help.' The journey from admission to treatment wasn't straightforward. Her parents' initial response mixed concern with denial‚Äîtheir daughter couldn't have anxiety; she was successful! Finding a therapist who accepted their insurance took weeks. The first medication caused unbearable side effects; the second took months to show improvement. Throughout, Ivy continued maintaining appearances, telling only her closest friend about her diagnosis. Gradually, therapy taught her to recognize anxiety's patterns, challenge catastrophic thinking, and accept imperfection. Medication stabilized her brain chemistry enough to apply these techniques. Most transformatively, Ivy began speaking openly about her experience‚Äîand discovered how many peers suffered silently, believing they were alone. Her advocacy made others' paths to treatment shorter than her own had been.",
