                title: "The Suffragettes (U)",
                text: "Emmeline Hartley was twenty-three when she was arrested for the first time, in 1910, outside Parliament. Her crime: demanding the right to vote. The subsequent imprisonment‚Äîforce-feeding when she hunger-struck, solitary confinement in freezing cells‚Äîwould have broken many. Instead, it forged her into an instrument of history. The suffragette movement had tried respectable tactics for decades. Petitions were ignored; peaceful demonstrations dismissed. By 1910, escalation seemed the only path forward. Emmeline joined window-smashing campaigns, arson attacks on empty buildings, anything to force public attention toward women's exclusion from democracy. Her family disowned her. The newspapers called her hysterical, unnatural, dangerous. Male politicians sneered that women were too emotional for political participation‚Äîwhile ordering brutal treatment of peaceful protesters. The irony was apparently lost on them. Prison became a revolving door. Emmeline was arrested seven times over four years. Each incarceration strengthened her resolve and weakened her body. The force-feedings left permanent damage to her throat and digestive system. She watched friends die from similar treatment. When World War I began in 1914, suffragettes suspended their campaign to support the war effort. Their contribution‚Äîworking in factories, serving as nurses, keeping society functioning while men fought‚Äîfinally demonstrated women's capabilities beyond domestic spheres. In 1918, women over thirty gained voting rights. Full equality came in 1928‚Äîtoo late for Emmeline, who died in 1926, body broken but spirit triumphant.",
