                title: "Dark Matter: The Invisible Universe (U)",
                text: "Everything humanity has ever observed‚Äîstars, planets, galaxies, ourselves‚Äîcomprises only about 5% of the universe's total content. The remaining 95% consists of dark matter and dark energy, neither of which we can see, touch, or directly detect. Understanding these invisible components has become modern physics' central challenge. Dark matter was first proposed in the 1930s when astronomer Fritz Zwicky noticed that galaxy clusters moved as if containing far more mass than their visible stars could account for. Subsequent observations confirmed this discrepancy everywhere: galaxies rotate too fast, gravitational lensing is too strong, cosmic structures formed too quickly. Something massive and invisible pervades the universe. Candidates for dark matter abound. Weakly Interacting Massive Particles (WIMPs) were long favored‚Äîhypothetical particles responding to gravity but ignoring normal matter. Despite decades of increasingly sensitive experiments, WIMPs haven't been found. Alternative theories propose modifications to gravitational physics itself rather than new particles. Dark energy presents an even deeper mystery. Discovered in 1998, it's the name given to whatever causes universal expansion to accelerate. Unlike dark matter, which attracts gravitationally, dark energy seems to push‚Äîa repulsive force growing stronger as the universe expands. Some theories connect it to quantum vacuum energy; others propose entirely new physics. The stakes extend beyond academic curiosity. Dark energy's ultimate fate determines whether the universe continues expanding forever, eventually tears itself apart, or somehow reverses. Our cosmic destiny depends on understanding forces we cannot see.",
