                title: "Plastic Pollution: A Global Crisis (U)",
                text: "Since mass production began in the 1950s, humanity has produced approximately 8.3 billion metric tons of plastic. Of this, roughly 6.3 billion tons have become waste‚Äîand 79% of that waste has accumulated in landfills or the natural environment. Plastic pollution now permeates every ecosystem on Earth, from ocean trenches to mountain peaks, with consequences we are only beginning to understand. Plastics persist because their chemical structures resist natural decomposition. A plastic bottle discarded today may still exist in recognizable form centuries from now. Rather than disappearing, larger plastics fragment into microplastics‚Äîparticles smaller than five millimeters‚Äîand nanoplastics measured in billionths of meters. These particles have been found in drinking water, seafood, table salt, and human blood. Marine impacts are particularly severe. An estimated 8 million metric tons of plastic enter oceans annually. Marine animals ingest plastic, mistaking it for food, suffering starvation as indigestible material fills their stomachs. Larger animals become entangled in debris. Coral reefs smothered by plastic bags experience disease rates twenty times higher than clean reefs. Solutions require addressing the entire plastic lifecycle. Reducing production, particularly of single-use items, prevents pollution at its source. Improved waste management systems capture plastic before it reaches the environment. Recycling, though often overstated as a solution, can reduce virgin plastic demand. Promising technologies may eventually enable plastic breakdown, though none currently operate at meaningful scale. The fundamental challenge is economic: plastic is cheap precisely because its environmental costs are externalized.",
