                title: "Prison Reform: Rethinking Incarceration (U)",
                text: "The United States incarcerates more people than any other nation‚Äîapproximately 2 million in prisons and jails, with millions more under correctional supervision. This mass incarceration has proven extraordinarily expensive, racially disproportionate, and largely ineffective at reducing crime. Growing recognition of these failures has sparked reform movements across the political spectrum. The current system emerged from 1970s-era 'tough on crime' policies that mandated long sentences for drug offenses, limited judicial discretion, and emphasized punishment over rehabilitation. Prison populations grew 500% over four decades while violent crime rates fluctuated independently. The correlation between incarceration and public safety proved far weaker than proponents claimed. Costs are staggering. Housing a prisoner costs states $25,000 to $60,000 annually‚Äîoften more than college tuition. Prison construction and operation consume resources that might fund education, mental health services, or drug treatment programs that actually reduce crime. Beyond direct costs, incarceration devastates families and communities, creating intergenerational cycles of disadvantage. Racial disparities pervade the system. Black Americans are incarcerated at five times the rate of whites, despite similar rates of drug use and criminal behavior. Disparities appear at every stage: arrest, charging, bail setting, conviction, and sentencing. These patterns perpetuate historical injustices while undermining system legitimacy. Reform proposals range from modest to transformative: reducing sentences for nonviolent offenses, eliminating cash bail that punishes poverty, investing in rehabilitation programs, decriminalizing drug use, exploring alternatives to incarceration entirely. Progress requires overcoming political fear of appearing 'soft on crime.'",
