                text: "The distress beacon activated 400 miles north of the Arctic Circle, where a Russian research vessel had become trapped in ice during an unexpected early freeze. Twenty-three scientists and crew faced dwindling supplies, crushing pressure from the shifting ice pack, and temperatures dropping toward minus fifty degrees Celsius. An international rescue mission assembled within hours, coordinating assets from Russia, Canada, Norway, and the United States. Dr. Amelia Torres commanded the American icebreaker Resilience, tasked with clearing a path through ice that had already claimed one rescue helicopter to mechanical failure in the extreme cold. The journey took six days through conditions Amelia had never encountered in thirty years of Arctic service. Pack ice exceeded fifteen feet thick in places, requiring repeated ramming to break through. Navigation relied on satellite imagery updated hourly as shifting ice constantly altered available routes. Her crew worked in four-hour shifts‚Äîlonger exposure risked frostbite despite protective gear. They reached the stranded vessel to find conditions worse than reported. The ship's hull had been breached; compartments were flooding with frigid seawater. Some crew members showed early hypothermia symptoms. The ice that trapped them now threatened to crush them entirely. Evacuation required transferring personnel across unstable ice floes while avoiding pressure ridges that could swallow a person in seconds. Amelia personally guided the final group, including an injured researcher who couldn't walk, as ice groaned and shifted beneath them. All twenty-three were rescued‚Äîbarely.",
