                text: "In a world where emotions could be extracted, stored, and sold, Elena made her living as a dealer in rare feelings. Most clients wanted joy, contentment, or romantic love‚Äîpredictable choices for predictable people. Elena specialized in harder merchandise: genuine wonder, artistic inspiration, that particular melancholy that makes autumn evenings beautiful. The extraction process was painless but permanent. Once sold, an emotion could never be naturally experienced again. Wealthy clients accumulated positive feelings while disposing of negative ones; the resulting emotional imbalance often proved catastrophic, but by then Elena had moved on. Her supplier was a hospice nurse who collected emotions from dying patients‚Äîpeople who no longer needed their feelings and welcomed the income for their families. It was legal, ethical by most standards, yet Elena sometimes wondered whether emotions truly belonged to individuals or were somehow communal property, meant to be experienced rather than hoarded. The question became urgent when a government official approached her seeking a specific commodity: authentic moral conviction. He intended to use purchased conviction to justify policies he privately knew were wrong‚Äîto feel righteous without being righteous. Elena had sold questionable merchandise before, but this request crystallized something. She refused, then began quietly returning extracted emotions to people who'd sold them in desperation, watching recipients rediscover feelings they'd thought lost forever. The business collapsed; Elena didn't care. Some transactions were too toxic to complete at any price.",
