                title: "Superbugs: The Antibiotic Crisis (V)",
                text: "Alexander Fleming's 1928 discovery of penicillin launched an era in which bacterial infections, previously major killers, became routinely curable. Ninety years later, antibiotic resistance threatens to reverse this medical revolution, creating 'superbugs' impervious to available treatments. Understanding how resistance emerges‚Äîand what can be done‚Äîis now a global health priority. Bacteria evolve resistance through natural selection. When antibiotics kill susceptible bacteria, resistant mutations survive and reproduce. Each antibiotic use creates selection pressure favoring resistance. Overuse accelerates this process: antibiotics prescribed for viral infections (which they don't affect), used as agricultural growth promoters, or taken incompletely (allowing resistant strains to survive) all contribute to the problem. The scale is alarming. Approximately 700,000 people die annually from drug-resistant infections‚Äîa number projected to reach 10 million by 2050 without intervention. Some bacteria now resist all available antibiotics, making infections that were treatable decades ago potentially fatal again. Routine surgeries become dangerous when post-operative infections can't be controlled. Pharmaceutical economics worsen the situation. Developing new antibiotics requires billions of dollars and years of research, yet successful drugs should be used sparingly to preserve effectiveness‚Äîa business model that discourages investment. Antibiotic pipelines have contracted while resistance has expanded. Solutions require coordinated action. Reducing unnecessary prescriptions, restricting agricultural antibiotic use, improving sanitation to prevent infections, and funding new drug development all contribute. International cooperation is essential since resistance genes spread globally. The stakes are existential: modern medicine's foundation depends on maintaining antibiotic effectiveness.",
