                title: "The Berlin Wall (W)",
                text: "For twenty-eight years, the Berlin Wall divided not just a city but families, ideologies, and visions of human possibility. When it fell on November 9, 1989, crowds that had lived under its shadow their entire lives streamed through checkpoints in disbelief. Among them was Helga M√ºller, who hadn't seen her sister in nearly three decades. Helga had been seventeen in 1961 when East Germany erected the Wall virtually overnight. Her sister Greta, twenty-two, happened to be visiting friends in West Berlin that weekend. They assumed the barrier would be temporary‚Äîa political maneuver that would resolve within weeks. Instead, it became permanent. Communication was restricted; visits nearly impossible. Over decades, Helga aged under communist surveillance while Greta built a new life in the West. They exchanged occasional letters, each word chosen carefully to pass censors. They spoke by phone twice annually, conversations monitored by state security. Their mother died in the East without Greta able to attend the funeral; authorities rejected her visa application. When the Wall opened, Helga was sixty-four. She walked through Checkpoint Charlie and found Greta waiting on the other side‚Äîalso sixty-four now, a stranger who shared her blood and her memories but little else. Their embrace lasted several minutes, neither willing to let go again. The sisters spent the following months learning who the other had become. Some differences couldn't be bridged; too much history had diverged. But they'd been reunited, and that was enough. The Wall had taken their youth; it couldn't have their remaining years.",
