                title: "Privacy in the Digital Age (W)",
                text: "Every smartphone user carries a surveillance device more powerful than anything totalitarian regimes of the past could have imagined. This device tracks location continuously, records communications, monitors purchasing patterns, and shares this information with corporations whose business models depend on knowing users intimately. Privacy, once assumed as a default condition, has become something that must be actively‚Äîand often expensively‚Äîmaintained. The data economy operates through asymmetric knowledge. Companies know far more about users than users know about companies or even about what information they've surrendered. Terms of service agreements that nobody reads grant broad permissions for data collection, analysis, and sale. The 'free' services people depend upon are paid for with information whose value users cannot accurately assess. Consequences extend beyond targeted advertising. Data brokers compile dossiers combining financial records, health information, social media activity, and location history‚Äîprofiles available to employers, insurers, landlords, and government agencies. Algorithmic systems make consequential decisions about creditworthiness, employment, and insurance based on data individuals never knowingly provided and often cannot access or correct. Legal frameworks lag behind technical capabilities. Privacy regulations like GDPR provide limited protections in some jurisdictions while leaving most of the world unregulated. The Constitutional right to privacy, developed before digital technology existed, offers uncertain guidance for contemporary challenges. Some scholars argue that meaningful privacy has become impossible absent fundamental restructuring of the data economy‚Äîa transformation that powerful interests strongly oppose.",
