                text: "The formal colonial era ended decades ago, but its consequences shape contemporary global politics, economics, and culture in ways that demand examination. Understanding how colonialism's legacies persist‚Äîand how different societies grapple with this inheritance‚Äîis essential for addressing present inequalities and historical injustices. European colonialism operated through extraction: removing resources, labor, and wealth from colonized territories to enrich imperial powers. Colonial boundaries, drawn without regard for existing communities, created nations grouping hostile ethnic groups while dividing unified peoples. Colonial education systems denigrated indigenous knowledge while imposing European languages and values. Colonial legal frameworks privileged settlers while dispossessing original inhabitants. These structures didn't disappear when flags changed. Many former colonies inherited economies designed to export raw materials rather than develop domestically, infrastructure connecting resources to ports rather than communities to each other, and institutions reflecting colonial priorities rather than local needs. Elite networks often preserved colonial-era power relations. The psychological dimensions are equally significant. Colonialism systematically devalued colonized peoples' cultures, histories, and capabilities, creating internalized oppression that persists across generations. Movements for decolonization extend beyond political independence to cultural recovery, historical reclamation, and psychological liberation. Reckoning with colonialism remains contentious. Debates about reparations, museum artifacts, educational curricula, and memorial landscapes reveal fundamental disagreements about responsibility and redress. Some argue that dwelling on historical injustice impedes progress; others contend that genuine progress requires honest confrontation with the past.",
