                id: 258,
                title: "Addiction (X)",
                text: "Nobody decides to become addicted. Seventeen-year-old Trevor had been a promising student with academic scholarships pending when the prescription for post-surgery pain medication began something he never anticipated. What started as legitimate treatment for a football injury became chemical dependence that consumed his senior year and nearly his life. The progression was insidious. After surgery, opioids provided relief not just from physical pain but from anxiety, depression, and adolescent uncertainty he hadn't known how to name. When the prescription ended, withdrawal was miserable‚Äîflu-like symptoms accompanied by cravings that felt indistinguishable from need. He found other sources: friends' medicine cabinets, eventually dealers offering pills, finally heroin when pills became too expensive. His family noticed changes‚Äîgrades dropping, friends changing, money disappearing‚Äîbut Trevor had become skilled at concealment and manipulation. Addicted brains excel at protecting their supply, even at the cost of relationships that would have seemed sacred before. His parents oscillated between enabling and tough love, receiving contradictory advice about how to help someone who couldn't or wouldn't help himself. The overdose that nearly killed him finally penetrated denial. Naloxone administered by paramedics reversed respiratory failure; intensive care treatment addressed the physical crisis. But recovery required confronting everything addiction had allowed him to avoid: the anxiety he had medicated, the relationships he had damaged, the future he had compromised. Treatment wasn't linear. Relapse is common in addiction recovery; Trevor experienced setbacks that tested everyone's patience. But gradually, through medication-assisted treatment, therapy, and support groups, he built tools for managing cravings and addressing underlying issues. Recovery became not a destination but an ongoing process requiring daily attention.",
